    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-26T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-26T05:00:00-05:00" n="665"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d665">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12978: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-26T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 26, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 26—8:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>96. Legation’s 87, February 23, 4 p.m. Following telegram has been received from
                    the Consul General at Hankow: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“February 26, noon. My February 23, noon, paragraph 2. In reply to my
                            telegram of 22nd, Shensi Government telegraphed 25th that it had
                            telegraphed General Sun Wei Ju to circularize his officers and men to
                            afford adequate protection to the missionaries of the various countries.
                            Also that telegrams had been sent to the various magistrates instructing
                            them to afford protection to American missionaries and other residents
                            and that when necessary they be escorted to places of safety.</p>
                        <p>A reply from the Kansu Government of February 24th states Red brigands
                            not threatening south Kansu.</p>
                        <p>A telegram from Shenminhsien, Kansu states they are preparing for
                            evacuation when necessary and that there is no apparent danger yet.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
